					<description><![CDATA[<p>Find out the fundamentals behind Google Ads keyword prioritization and a breakdown of what Google's prioritization rules mean for small business advertisers. </p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/keyword-prioritization">How Keyword Prioritization Works in Google Ads (+What It Means)</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Have you ever looked at your search terms report and thought, ‚ÄúWhat the heck is that search doing in that campaign?‚Äù</p>
<p>Or have you seen a previously top-performing search campaign virtually stop spending when you launch Performance Max?</p>
<p>Google recently updated and clarified what it calls <a href="https://support.google.com/google-ads/answer/2756257?hl=en">keyword and search theme prioritization</a> and if you haven‚Äôt yet seen the delightfully confusing chart we&#8217;ll cover below, don‚Äôt worry. I‚Äôm going to break it down for you right now, clear and simple, plus share what it means for your Google Ads account.</p>
<h3>Contents</h3>
<ul>
<li><a href="#what-is-keyword-prioritization">What is keyword prioritization?</a></li>
<li><a href="#keyword-matching">What&#8217;s the difference between keyword matching and keyword prioritization?</a></li>
<li><a href="#google-ads-keyword-prioritization-rules">5 things to know about the Google Ads keyword prioritization rules</a></li>
<li><a href="#what-keyword-prioritization-means">What keyword prioritization means for small business advertisers</a></li>
</ul>
<div id="what-is-keyword-prioritization"></div>
<h2>What is Google Ads keyword prioritization?</h2>
<p><a href="https://localiq.com/blog/keyword-research-for-ppc/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Keyword</a> prioritization is how Google chooses which of your ads to show when a user searches for something that‚Äôs relevant to your business.</p>
<p>Remember, there are a whole bunch of different ways that your search and<a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/07/05/performance-max-tips" target="_blank" rel="noopener"> Performance Max ads</a> can matched to user queries, including:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Keywords </strong>added to a search campaign in<a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/google-ads-query-matching-updates" target="_blank" rel="noopener"> broad, phrase, or exact match</a>.</li>
<li><a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/12/11/search-themes-for-performance-max-campaigns" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>Search themes</strong></a> added to a Performance Max campaign.</li>
<li><strong>Dynamic ad targets</strong> added to a dynamic ad group in a search campaign.</li>
<li><strong>AI-matching</strong> for Performance Max campaigns without search themes.</li>
</ul>
<p>For simplicity‚Äôs sake, the rest of this article will simply say ‚Äúkeywords‚Äù to refer to any of the ways you become eligible to show ads on Google Search: keywords, search themes, dynamic ad targets, or AI-matching.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/google-ads-keyword-prioritization-report.webp" alt="google ads keyword prioritization chart" width="484" height="650" class="aligncenter wp-image-86158 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/google-ads-keyword-prioritization-report.webp 484w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/google-ads-keyword-prioritization-report-480x645.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 484px, 100vw" /></p>
<div id="keyword-matching"></div>
<h3>What‚Äôs the difference between keyword matching and keyword prioritization in Google Ads?</h3>
<p>Keyword matching, using<a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/10/13/future-of-keyword-match-types" target="_blank" rel="noopener"> keyword match types</a>, is a system that figures out whether or not you‚Äôre eligible to show an ad on a user‚Äôs search.</p>
<p>Because of <a href="https://support.google.com/google-ads/answer/7478529?hl=en" target="_blank" rel="noopener">how keyword matching works</a>, it‚Äôs common to have multiple keywords in your account that can match with the same query. However, you can only show one search ad at a time.</p>
<p>For example, let‚Äôs say a user searches for ‚Äúled lightbulbs.‚Äù That could match to:</p>
<ul>
<li>Your generic lightbulb search campaign, which has the keyword ‚Äúlightbulb.‚Äù</li>
<li>Your discount lightbulb search campaign, which has the keyword [led lightbulbs on sale].</li>
<li>Your dynamic ad group in a search campaign, which has ad targets on all of your LED lightbulb product pages.</li>
</ul>
<p>How will Google determine which campaign ‚Äúwins‚Äù and shows an ad?</p>
<p>That‚Äôs where keyword prioritization comes in. When multiple ads are eligible to match to a user‚Äôs query, an elaborate AI-powered keyword prioritization occurs to determine which campaign, ad group, keyword, and ad are ‚Äúput forward‚Äù into the auction, to compete for that user‚Äôs click.</p>
<p><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/1f50d.png" alt="üîç" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> Optimize your keyword list to align with your business&#8217;s priorities using our <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/keywords?cid=Web_Any_InContentTextLink_Keywords_KWTool" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Free Keyword Tool</a>.</p>
<div id="google-ads-keyword-prioritization-rules"></div>
<h2>5 things to know about the Google Ads keyword prioritization rules</h2>
<p>Here are the five pillars of Google Ads keyword prioritization.</p>
<h3>1. Exact match keywords get top priority</h3>
<p>If you have an eligible exact match keyword identical to the user‚Äôs query, it will be prioritized and enter the auction above any other keywords. Think of this like ‚Äúold school‚Äù exact match still winning the day.</p>
<p>Remember, the definition of exact match today is that the user‚Äôs query must match <em>the intent or meaning</em> of your keyword. For example, if you have the keyword [google ads tool], and the user searches for ‚ÄúAdWords tool,‚Äù that would be considered an exact match (close variant), since ‚Äú<em>google ads</em>‚Äù and ‚Äú<em>adwords</em>‚Äù are synonyms. According to keyword matching rules, you would be eligible to show an ad.</p>
<p>But from a prioritization perspective, ‚Äú<em>google ads</em>‚Äù and ‚Äú<em>Adwords</em>‚Äù do not exactly match‚Äîthey are not identical. So, your [google ads tool] keyword would not automatically move forward to the auction, especially if you have a keyword like ‚Äú<em>adwords tool</em>‚Äù or even ‚Äú<em>google ads tool</em>‚Äù elsewhere in your account.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/keyword-prioritization-exact-match.webp" alt="keyword prioritization - exact match" width="664" height="243" class="aligncenter wp-image-86161 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/keyword-prioritization-exact-match.webp 664w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/keyword-prioritization-exact-match-480x176.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 664px, 100vw" /></p>
<h3>2. The only time exact match means an<em> identical</em> match</h3>
<p>It‚Äôs clear that ‚Äú<em>google ads tool</em>‚Äù and ‚Äú<em>adwords tool</em>‚Äù are not identical. But what about ‚Äú<em>google ads tool</em>‚Äù and ‚Äú<em>google ads tools</em>,‚Äù the singular versus plural? Or, ‚Äú<em>google ads tool</em>‚Äù versus a 1-letter misspelling, such as ‚Äú<em>gogle ads tool</em>.&#8221;</p>
<p>While synonyms, misspellings, and plural iterations of keywords can all ‚Äúmatch‚Äù to exact match keywords, they are treated differently when we‚Äôre talking about keyword prioritization.</p>
<ul>
<li><b>Synonyms (google ads versus adwords): Not an identical match, will not receive top priority if it matches an exact match keyword.</b></li>
<li><strong>Misspellings</strong><strong> (google ads versus gogle ads):</strong> Considered an identical match, will receive top priority when it matches an exact match keyword.</li>
<li><strong>Plurals</strong><strong> (google ads tool versus google ads tools):</strong> Not an identical match, will not receive top priority if it matches an exact match keyword.</li>
</ul>
<p>And what if we‚Äôre evaluating ‚Äú<em>google ads</em>‚Äù versus ‚Äú<em>google ad</em>,‚Äù which could be considered a synonym, misspelling, or plural? Who knows!</p>
<p>I‚Äôm serious. The best piece of advice I can give you to wrap your head around keyword prioritization rules is to think of them as a helpful guide when <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/05/10/google-ads-account-structure" target="_blank" rel="noopener">planning your campaign structure</a>, but acknowledge that no matter what, this will all be a bit fuzzy in practice.</p>
<h3>3. Phrase match, broad match, and search themes share second place</h3>
<p>Now that we understand that exact match keywords get top priority when the keyword is identical to the user‚Äôs search, what happens when you don‚Äôt have an identical exact match keyword?</p>
<p><a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ehanced-cpc-going-away">Google Ads</a> will look for a phrase match keyword, a <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2015/04/03/broad-match-type" target="_blank" rel="noopener">broad match</a> keyword, or a Performance Max search theme that is identical to the user‚Äôs search.</p>
<p>When we say ‚Äúidentical,‚Äù the same rules apply as above: the actual letters and words of your keyword/search themes exactly match what the user typed, including misspellings, not including synonyms or plurals.</p>
<p>For example, if the user searches for ‚Äú<em>google ads tool</em>,‚Äù and you have the keywords in your account [<em>google ads</em>] and ‚Äú<em>google ads tol</em>,‚Äù and the Performance Max search theme ‚Äú<em>google ads tool</em>,‚Äù the phrase match misspelled keyword ‚Äú<em>google ads tol</em>‚Äù and the Performance Max search theme ‚Äú<em>google ads tool</em>‚Äù would be prioritized. The exact match non-identical keyword [google ads] is not an option for this auction.</p>
<p>In this example, which ad would move forward to the <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2011/11/16/how-adwords-works" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Google Ads auction</a>: the search ad with the misspelled phrase match keyword, or the Performance Max ad with the identical search theme?</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/keyword-prioritization-broad-match.webp" alt="google ads keyword prioritization - phrase and broad match" width="664" height="215" class="aligncenter wp-image-86162 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/keyword-prioritization-broad-match.webp 664w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/keyword-prioritization-broad-match-480x155.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 664px, 100vw" /></p>
<h3>4. Ad rank still matters in Google Ads‚Äîa lot</h3>
<p>When you have multiple keywords or search themes at the same prioritization level, the one with the highest ad rank will move forward to the auction.</p>
<p><a href="https://support.google.com/google-ads/answer/1722122?hl=en" target="_blank" rel="noopener">What‚Äôs ad rank, again</a>? The simplified answer for our purposes right now is that ad rank is a calculation of your bids and your <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/07/19/does-quality-score-still-matter" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Quality Score</a>. The higher your bids, the higher your ad rank, and the more likely you are to enter the auction (and, hopefully, win the auction). The higher the quality of your ads, the more likely you are to enter and win the auction as well.</p>
<p>Therefore, when multiple campaigns in your account are eligible to show an ad and sit at the same prioritization level, the one with the higher ad rank will move forward to the auction and compete to show your ad.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/google-ads-keyword-prioritization-ad-rank.webp" alt="keyword prioritization - ad rank" width="664" height="197" class="aligncenter wp-image-86163 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/google-ads-keyword-prioritization-ad-rank.webp 664w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/google-ads-keyword-prioritization-ad-rank-480x142.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 664px, 100vw" /></p>
<h3>5. AI-powered keyword prioritization: the newest part</h3>
<p>You can‚Äôt talk about new Google Ads features anymore without <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ai-in-marketing" target="_blank" rel="noopener">talking about AI</a>, so let‚Äôs dig into how artificial intelligence powers keyword prioritization today.</p>
<p>Let‚Äôs be honest: although we‚Äôve spent a lot of time discussing what happens with identical matches, the most likely scenario in your account is going to be that the user‚Äôs search is <em>not identical </em>to an existing keyword or search theme. This means it <em>could</em> match to many of your keywords, search themes, and dynamic ad targets.</p>
<p>Enter AI. AI-based keyword prioritization will look at every eligible kind of targeting in your account, including:</p>
<ul>
<li>Keywords</li>
<li>Dynamic ad targets</li>
<li>Search themes</li>
<li>Performance Max campaigns without search themes</li>
</ul>
<p>and choose the most relevant ones to be considered in the auction.</p>
<p>‚ÄúRelevant‚Äù doesn‚Äôt mean ‚Äúhow identical it is to the keyword.‚Äù Relevant also doesn‚Äôt mean <a href="https://support.google.com/google-ads/answer/6167118?hl=en" target="_blank" rel="noopener">ad relevance</a>, the component of Quality Score that looks at the relationship between the user‚Äôs search and your ad.</p>
<p>For AI-based keyword prioritization, relevance looks at the <em>meaning</em> of the user‚Äôs search, all the keywords in an ad group, and the landing pages within the ad group. From there, machine learning would figure out which ad is most likely to entice that user‚Äôs click.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/keyword-prioritization-ai.webp" alt="keyword prioritization - ai" width="664" height="349" class="aligncenter wp-image-86160 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/keyword-prioritization-ai.webp 664w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/keyword-prioritization-ai-480x252.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 664px, 100vw" /></p>
<p><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/1f6a8.png" alt="üö®" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> Get ideas to optimize your account&#8217;s keyword lists and more with our free<a href="https://www.wordstream.com/google-adwords?cid=Web_Any_InContentTextLink_PPC_AWGrader_AWGrader" target="_blank" rel="noopener"> Google Ads Grader</a>!</p>
<div id="what-keyword-prioritization-means"></div>
<h2>What this means: 3 implications of the Google Ads keyword prioritization rules</h2>
<p>Full disclosure: we are now shifting from Google Ads facts to Jyll Saskin Gales&#8217; opinions. There are many potential implications of Google‚Äôs keyword prioritization rules. Here are three I‚Äôd like you to consider:</p>
<h3>1. Lack of control in keyword prioritization</h3>
<p>First, <strong>you have less control than you think</strong> over what searches you advertise on. Those that embrace automation with a consolidated campaign structure, providing sufficient budget and data integration to power Google‚Äôs AI, will see better results over the long term than those that attempt to cling to control. Sure, you could respond to this news by adding thousands of exact match keywords to your account and manually bidding, but you will spend all your time battling negatives and fiddling with bid adjustments, fighting the machine rather than getting the machine working for you. That doesn‚Äôt sound like fun or success to me.</p>
<h3>2. Dynamic Search Ads are less of a priority</h3>
<p>Second, <strong>Dynamic Search Ads are shafted</strong> in prioritization. For the record, they are also shafted in the search campaign setup process. You can‚Äôt create a dynamic ad group in the current Search campaign setup process; you can only add one <em>after</em> the campaign has been created with a standard ad group. Given this and the fact that the search component of Performance Max is already powered by DSAs, I predict that dynamic ad groups will be ‚Äúupgraded‚Äù to Performance Max soon. If you‚Äôre an advertiser who leverages a lot of DSAs, you may want to start testing alternate strategies, like broad-match keywords with<a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/04/05/responsive-search-ad-copy" target="_blank" rel="noopener"> responsive search ads</a>.</p>
<h3>3. Ad rank still matters</h3>
<p>Third, <strong>ad rank is still one of the most important factors </strong>in Google Ads success. While factors like auction competition, user context, and ad assets all matter too, it&#8217;s important to remember that you have the most control over are still your bids and your Quality Score to improve your ad rank regardless of the queries you match with. That‚Äôs the funny thing about Google Ads‚Äîas much as features and tools change over time, the fundamentals, like Quality Score and <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2018/12/19/google-ads-automated-bidding" target="_blank" rel="noopener">bid strategy</a>, still remain the same.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/google-ads-ad-rank-formula.webp" alt="google ads ad rank formula" width="900" height="283" class="aligncenter wp-image-86159 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/google-ads-ad-rank-formula.webp 900w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/google-ads-ad-rank-formula-480x151.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 900px, 100vw" /></p>
<h2>When optimizing your keyword lists, consider Google Ads keyword prioritization</h2>
<p>It can be easy to only focus on your keyword match type mix without considering how Google Ads keyword prioritization can also impact what queries your ads match with. Be sure to save the walkthrough above when you need to quickly predict how your core keywords could align with potential searches (and include it in your <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/google-ads-audit">Google Ads audits</a>). For more help making the most out of your Google Ads keywords, see how <a href="https://localiq.com/demo?cid=Web_LiQ_Any_InContent_Demo_Blog_Demo" target="_blank" rel="noopener">our solutions</a> can maximize your Google Ads campaign success.</p>
