]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
			</item>
		<item>
		<title>How to Use the Google Ads Library to Spy on Competitors</title>
		<link>https://www.wordstream.com/blog/google-ads-library</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Jyll Saskin Gales]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Mon, 05 Feb 2024 12:30:14 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Google Ads]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Paid Search Marketing]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://www.wordstream.com/?p=79826</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[<p>Become a super spy and get sleuthing to improve your ads using the Google Ads library (AKA the Google Ads Transparency Center).</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/google-ads-library">How to Use the Google Ads Library to Spy on Competitors</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Let‚Äôs go spy on some Google Ads!</p>
<p><span>How? Google expanded the new Ads Transparency Center, colloquially known as the Google Ads Library.</span></p>
<p><span>This means that Google now has a searchable ads library, just like Meta and TikTok! This is an exciting and long overdue development for Google Ads practitioners, as we can now quickly find text, image, and video ad inspiration for our campaigns.</span></p>
<p><span>And spy on our competitors, of course.</span></p>
<h3><strong>Table of contents</strong></h3>
<ul>
<li><a href="#how-to-use-the-google-ads-library">How to use the Google Ads library</a></li>
<li><a href="#find-competitors-on-google-ads-library">How to use the Google Ads library to find your competitors&#8217; ads</a></li>
<li><a href="#find-ad-information-on-google-ads-transparency-center">Another way to use the Google Ads Transparency Center to find ad information</a></li>
<li><a href="#google-ads-library-verification">Google Ads library and advertiser verification: What you need to know</a></li>
</ul>
<div id="how-to-use-the-google-ads-library"></div>
<h2>How to use the Google Ads library</h2>
<p><span>The first thing to know about the Google Ads library is that it is not actually called the Google Ads library. Instead, you can find all active ads through the <a href="https://adstransparency.google.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Google Ads Transparency Center</a>.</span></p>
<h3>Search for ads using the Google Ads library</h3>
<p><span>When searching for ads, you can search by advertiser name or by website URL. I find the website URL search to be much easier and more accurate than trying to weed through advertiser names, since many companies may be verified through a parent company or through their agency.</span></p>
<p><span>For example, if you try to find ads for the clothing company Gap, you‚Äôll find a whole range of companies with ‚ÄúGap‚Äù in their name, but not <em>the</em> Gap.</span></p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/google-ad-library-google-ads-transparency-center-home.jpg" alt="google ads library - google ads transparency center screenshot" width="864" height="454" class="aligncenter wp-image-79851 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/google-ad-library-google-ads-transparency-center-home.jpg 864w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/google-ad-library-google-ads-transparency-center-home-480x252.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 864px, 100vw" /></p>
<p><span>Add ‚Äú.com,‚Äù however, and it becomes quite clear which one is the Gap clothing company. As you can see, different domain suffixes, like .com vs. .co.uk vs. .ca, will come up separately when you use the website URL search.</span></p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/google-ads-library-search.jpg" alt="google ads library - refined google ad transparency search example" width="847" height="412" class="aligncenter wp-image-79856 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/google-ads-library-search.jpg 847w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/google-ads-library-search-480x233.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 847px, 100vw" /></p>
<p><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/1f4a1.png" alt="üí°" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> Find more ways to get ahead of your competition with our free <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/google-adwords?cid=Web_Any_InContentTextLink_PPC_AWGrader_AWGrader" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Google Ads Grader</a>!</p>
<h3>Filter Google Ads library results</h3>
<p><span>There are four filters you can use in the Google Ads library to help you find what you‚Äôre looking for: date range, geography, format, and all topics vs. political ads.</span></p>
<p><span>I recommend using the date range filter to look at the last 30 days, rather than ‚ÄúAny time,‚Äù when looking for ad inspiration. The exception would be if you have a specific reason you want to look back further in time. Perhaps you‚Äôd like to get inspiration for your Valentine‚Äôs Day ads by looking at ads that ran during last Valentine‚Äôs Day. </span></p>
<p><span>Next, there is a country filter. By default, the Google Ads Transparency Center will filter results to those ads that ran in your country, so be sure to adjust this if needed. For example, I&#8217;m in Canada and I often want to see what US-based advertisers are doing.</span></p>
<p><span>The third filter lets you search by ad format, image, text, or video. I find this feature to be a bit buggy, so I recommend keeping it on the default, which is all formats.</span></p>
<p><span>The final filter, all topics vs. political ads, works similarly to the <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/06/06/facebook-ad-library" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Meta Ads library</a>. You‚Äôre probably going to want to keep that one on all topics unless you‚Äôre managing some kind of political or cause-based campaign.</span></p>
<div id="find-competitors-on-google-ads-library"></div>
<h2>How to use the Google Ads library to find your competitors&#8217; ads</h2>
<p><span>To demonstrate how you can use the Google Ads library to find your competitors (and learn from their wins or mistakes!), let‚Äôs use the luxury athleisure company Lululemon as an example.</span></p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/google-ads-library-example.jpg" alt="google ads library - example of searching lululemon in google ads transparency center" width="836" height="547" class="aligncenter wp-image-79855 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/google-ads-library-example.jpg 836w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/google-ads-library-example-480x314.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 836px, 100vw" /></p>
<p><span>You‚Äôll notice that if I type in Lululemon, a whole bunch of verified advertisers and domains show up. This reflects how the business verified itself with Google.</span></p>
<p><span>I‚Äôm interested in <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/04/19/digital-marketing-statistics" target="_blank" rel="noopener">ads for the US market</a>, so I‚Äôm going to select the Lululemon.com domain. I could have also used trial and error to determine that the Canada-based ‚ÄúLululemon Athletica Canada Inc.‚Äù manages the US arm of the business.</span></p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/google-ad-library-see-all-ads.jpg" alt="google ads library - see all ads screenshot" width="797" height="528" class="aligncenter wp-image-79854 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/google-ad-library-see-all-ads.jpg 797w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/google-ad-library-see-all-ads-480x318.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 797px, 100vw" /></p>
<p><span>Initially, only a few ads show up when you select an advertiser, and already we can learn a lot about this Google Ads account. </span><span>For example, we now know that Lululemon is leveraging a variety of assets: sitelinks, logo, <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/02/23/how-to-come-up-with-a-business-name" target="_blank" rel="noopener">business name</a>, image, and ratings.</span></p>
<p><span>We can also see that they are<a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2020/07/29/how-to-promote-a-product" target="_blank" rel="noopener"> advertising a range of product lines</a> for both men and women.</span></p>
<p><span>By clicking ‚ÄúSee all ads‚Äù we can start to see thousands of examples of how Lululemon is advertising on Google right now.</span></p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/google-ads-library-preview.jpg" alt="google ads library - preview by country" width="823" height="545" class="aligncenter wp-image-79853 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/google-ads-library-preview.jpg 823w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/google-ads-library-preview-480x318.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 823px, 100vw" /></p>
<p><span>See that photo of a person stretching? That‚Äôs a <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/08/22/demand-gen-campaigns" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Discovery ad</a>, so we now know Lululemon is running either <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/05/01/is-performance-max-right-for-you" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Performance Max</a> or Demand Gen campaigns.</span></p>
<p><span>Showing a human in the center of the picture using the product is an effective way to use imagery in Google Ads; this outperforms static ‚Äúecommerce-style‚Äù images in Discovery placements via Performance Max and Demand Gen, according to Google‚Äôs internal research.</span></p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/google-ads-library-lululemon.jpg" alt="google ads library - google ad transparency center example search screenshot" width="804" height="536" class="aligncenter wp-image-79848 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/google-ads-library-lululemon.jpg 804w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/google-ads-library-lululemon-480x320.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 804px, 100vw" /></p>
<p><span>Scrolling down through the active ads, we see more examples of Search and Discovery placements, including a promotion asset and a Discovery carousel. </span></p>
<p><span>Next, I‚Äôm curious if Lululemon is leveraging video as part of their Google Ads strategy, so I turn on the video filter, and voila! Every video is there from their current brand campaigns, and I can click on any of them to watch for inspiration.</span></p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/google-ads-library-display-and-discovery.jpg" alt="google ads library - screenshot of display and demand gen discovery ads in google ads transparency center" width="780" height="542" class="aligncenter wp-image-79852 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/google-ads-library-display-and-discovery.jpg 780w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/google-ads-library-display-and-discovery-480x334.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 780px, 100vw" /></p>
<p><span>For example, this video ad below has four variations, in both</span> <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/06/03/how-to-advertise-on-youtube" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Display and YouTube placements</a>, which suggests it‚Äôs likely being used as an asset in a Performance Max campaign.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/google-ad-library-individual-ad.jpg" alt="google ad library - google transparency center individual ad details" width="788" height="535" class="aligncenter wp-image-79850 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/google-ad-library-individual-ad.jpg 788w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/google-ad-library-individual-ad-480x326.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 788px, 100vw" /></p>
<p><span>By viewing a company‚Äôs active ads and combining it with our knowledge of how Google Ads works, we can learn a lot about any advertiser‚Äôs <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/01/19/google-ads-for-small-businesses" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Google Ads strategy</a> from the Google Ads library.</span></p>
<p><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/1f331.png" alt="üå±" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> Accelerate your business&#8217;s growth and surpass your competitors with our free <a href="https://marketing.localiq.com/WSLIQContentDLWebsite7StepstoGrowthStrategy.html?cid=Web_WS_InContent_Guide_GrowthStrategy_Download" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Growth Strategy Guide</a>!</p>
<div id="find-ad-information-on-google-ads-transparency-center"></div>
<h2>Another way to find ad information on the Google Ads Transparency Center</h2>
<p><span>While a searchable Google Ads library is a dream come true for PPC practitioners, you can find out even more about a company‚Äôs ads when you are served those ads as a user. This is my favorite way to sneak a peek not just at what ads are running, but how various businesses are targeting their ads.</span></p>
<p><span>Whenever you see an ad on Google, whether it‚Äôs on Search, YouTube, Discovery, etc., tap the three dots in the top right-hand corner to pull up My Ad Center.</span></p>
<p><span>Scroll down to ‚ÄúWhy you‚Äôre seeing this ad‚Äù and take note of the targeting settings. Some options you may see include:</span></p>
<ul>
<li><span> </span><span>The time of day</span></li>
<li><span> </span><span>Your age</span></li>
<li><span> </span><span>Your current search terms</span></li>
<li><span> </span><span>Your general location (like your country or city)</span></li>
<li><span> </span><span>Google‚Äôs estimation of your approximate current location</span></li>
<li><span> </span><span>Google‚Äôs estimation of your areas of interest, based on your activity</span></li>
<li><span> </span><span>Information you gave to the advertiser, which the advertiser provided to Google</span></li>
<li><span> </span><span>Your similarity to groups of people the advertiser is trying to reach, according to your activity while you were signed in to Google</span></li>
</ul>
<p><span>This is a great way to <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/08/21/google-skillshop" target="_blank" rel="noopener">keep your Google Ads skills sharp</a>. As you‚Äôre passing time online, check out ‚Äúwhy you‚Äôre seeing this ad‚Äù and try to deduce the advertiser‚Äôs targeting settings and, if you can, campaign strategy.</span></p>
<p><span>For example, I was just served this Discovery ad on my phone from a company called Synthesis. I‚Äôd never heard of them before.</span></p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/google-ad-library-search-ad-example.jpg" alt="google ads library - example my ad center search ad" width="553" height="503" class="aligncenter wp-image-79849 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/google-ad-library-search-ad-example.jpg 553w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/google-ad-library-search-ad-example-480x437.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 553px, 100vw" /></p>
<p><span>My Ad Center tells me that Google thinks I‚Äôm interested in ‚Äútutoring services‚Äù (I‚Äôm not), and the ‚ÄúWhy you‚Äôre seeing this ad‚Äù section says that my age, location, and areas of interest were used to target this ad.</span></p>
<p><span>I‚Äôm a parent of a 5-year-old and a baby, and I was recently looking into swimming lessons, gymnastics lessons, and summer camps for my eldest. Yes, on Google Search. These activities likely flagged me as a prime candidate for online activities for my school-age child, though I think ‚Äútutoring services‚Äù is a stretch.</span></p>
<p><span>Personally, I find the headline ‚Äúyour child‚Äôs superhuman tutor‚Äù off-putting rather than enticing, but hey‚Äîthe algorithm will learn, since I didn‚Äôt engage with this ad.</span></p>
<p><span>Scrolling a bit further, the next ad I see is for a special offer to subscribe to The Times of London newspaper.</span></p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/google-ads-library-my-ad-center.jpg" alt="google ads library - my ad center" width="498" height="457" class="aligncenter wp-image-79862 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/google-ads-library-my-ad-center.jpg 498w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/google-ads-library-my-ad-center-480x440.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 498px, 100vw" /></p>
<p><span>My husband is British and subscribes to The Guardian, so I‚Äôm wondering if some signals got crossed in our household targeting. Let‚Äôs check out My Ad Center to see.</span></p>
<p><span>Apparently, Google thinks I‚Äôm interested in Newspapers (correct) and a brand called News UK.</span></p>
<p><span>I‚Äôm seeing this ad due to my location, areas of interest, and‚Äîaha!‚Äîmy similarity to people the advertiser is trying to reach.</span></p>
<p><span>Since we know that similar segments have been deprecated for a while, that means this advertiser is likely running this ad through a Demand Gen campaign, which offers a Lookalike targeting option. It would make sense for an English newspaper seeking new subscribers abroad to find people similar to existing international subscribers.</span></p>
<p><span>I see the number 12 everywhere in this ad, so it‚Äôs clear they think that the <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/10/27/brand-messaging" target="_blank" rel="noopener">‚Äúvalue‚Äù messaging</a> is enough to convert cold traffic. Time will tell if I end up subscribing! But I didn‚Äôt click on this ad, either.</span></p>
<div id="google-ads-library-verification"></div>
<h2>Advertiser verification and the Google Ads library: What you need to know</h2>
<p><span>We can‚Äôt complete our discussion of the Google Ads library and Google Ads Transparency Center without a word about <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/07/13/google-advertiser-verification" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Google Ads advertiser verification</a>.</span></p>
<p><span>If you<a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/05/10/google-ads-account-structure" target="_blank" rel="noopener"> manage a Google Ads account</a>, then you‚Äôll be familiar with the notification emails informing you that it‚Äôs time to verify your account. It‚Äôs usually a straightforward process, and you want to complete the steps promptly so that your account doesn‚Äôt get suspended.</span></p>
<p><span>The Google Ads library shows ads from Google Ads accounts that have completed advertiser verification. This means that you may not be able to see certain ads, if the accounts running those ads have not yet gone through the verification process.</span></p>
<h2>Gain insight (and a competitive edge) with the Google Ads library</h2>
<p>Clearly, the Google Ads library is a treasure trove of information regarding ads in your industry. With this tool, you can predict what types of Google Ads your <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/competitive-insights">competitors</a> are leveraging, and also get further insight from the My Ad Center. Learn even more tricks in this guide to <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/competitors-ads">spying on your competitors</a>. And if you find that your ads don&#8217;t currently align with what&#8217;s hot in the Google Ads library, see how<a href="https://www.wordstream.com/marketing-services" target="_blank" rel="noopener"> our solutions</a> can help you maximize your business&#8217;s Google Ads strategy!</p>
