		<item>
		<title>Meta Ads vs. Google Ads: 6 Key Differences (+Which Is Better?)</title>
		<link>https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/08/15/meta-ads-vs-google-ads</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Jyll Saskin Gales]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Tue, 15 Aug 2023 13:30:56 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Facebook Ads]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Paid Search Marketing]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://www.wordstream.com/?p=75208</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[<p>Meta Ads and Google Ads can both help you reach new audiences and connect with new customers on widely used platforms. But what are the major differences? We walk through what you need to know to decide which is best for your business. </p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/08/15/meta-ads-vs-google-ads">Meta Ads vs. Google Ads: 6 Key Differences (+Which Is Better?)</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>As a Google Ads coach, I‚Äôve noticed an increase recently in Meta Ads practitioners looking to start offering Google Ads services to their clients. By launching PPC campaigns across platforms, businesses are finding more opportunity to scale and stronger results.</p>
<p>While both Google and Meta‚Äôs ad platforms offer many of the same capabilities, there are fundamental differences that can trip you up when going from one to the other.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/meta-ads-vs-google-ads.jpg" alt="meta ads vs google ads logos" width="936" height="432" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-75221" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/meta-ads-vs-google-ads.jpg 936w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/meta-ads-vs-google-ads-480x222.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 936px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Here are the top differences I‚Äôve observed between Meta Ads vs. Google Ads in the campaign setup process broken down by:</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="#objective">Campaign objectives</a></li>
<li><a href="#placements">Platforms and placements</a></li>
<li><a href="#budgets">Budgets</a></li>
<li><a href="#creative">Creative</a></li>
<li><a href="#targeting">Targeting</a></li>
<li><a href="#reporting">Reporting</a></li>
</ul>
<p>Let&#8217;s dive in started.</p>
<div id="objective"></div>
<h2>Meta Ads vs. Google Ads: Campaign objectives</h2>
<p>In both ad platforms, when you create a new campaign, the first step is to pick your campaign objective.</p>
<p>In Meta Ads Manager, the campaign objective <em>is</em> the campaign type. For example, a Traffic campaign or an App promotion campaign will lead to fundamentally different setup processes and campaign capabilities.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/meta-ads-campaign-objective.jpg" alt="meta ads campaign objective in set up" width="642" height="600" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-75222" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/meta-ads-campaign-objective.jpg 642w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/meta-ads-campaign-objective-480x449.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 642px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>In Google Ads, selecting a campaign objective is optional and, in my opinion, not recommended. This selection allows Google to narrow the options available to you later in the setup process. For example, if you choose ‚ÄúBrand awareness and reach‚Äù as an objective, Google Ads will only let you select a Display or Video campaign type at the next step.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/google-ads-campaign-objective.jpg" alt="google ads campaign objective" width="936" height="525" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-75223" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/google-ads-campaign-objective.jpg 936w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/google-ads-campaign-objective-480x269.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 936px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Once you select a campaign objective (or not), the second step is to select a campaign type. This is where you‚Äôll choose between Search, Display, Performance Max, <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/06/12/google-discovery-ads-vs-display">Discovery</a>, etc.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/google-ads-campaign-type.jpg" alt="google ads campaign type in set up" width="936" height="487" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-75224" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/google-ads-campaign-type.jpg 936w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/google-ads-campaign-type-480x250.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 936px, 100vw" /></p>
<div id="placements"></div>
<h2>Meta Ads vs. Google Ads: Platforms and placements</h2>
<p>As you probably know, Google Ads allows you to set up Search campaigns so that you can show ads to people based on what they‚Äôre searching for. Meta Ads does not have a Search equivalent across its platforms like Facebook, Instagram, and WhatsApp.</p>
<p>However, it‚Äôs a common misconception that Google Ads only run on Google platforms like Search, <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2020/08/17/youtube-ad-placement-targeting">YouTube</a>, Gmail, etc. Google Ads can also run on Search partner sites (non-Google websites that use Google‚Äôs technology to power their on-site search). Video Ads can also run on video partner sites (similar concept). And of course, there‚Äôs the <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2020/03/16/google-display-network-mistakes">Google Display Network</a>, a collection of millions of websites that monetize using Google AdSense.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/google-ads-placements.jpg" alt="a few key google ads placements across the google display network" width="936" height="503" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-75215" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/google-ads-placements.jpg 936w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/google-ads-placements-480x258.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 936px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Meta‚Äôs version of the Google Display Network is called the <a href="https://www.facebook.com/business/help/788333711222886" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Meta Audience Network</a>, and it works similarly. In a Meta Ads campaign, you can manually select your various platforms and networks, or just let Meta optimize this for you.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/meta-ads-placement.jpg" alt="a few key meta ads placement options" width="936" height="310" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-75214" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/meta-ads-placement.jpg 936w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/meta-ads-placement-480x159.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 936px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>A few key Meta Ads placement options.</em></p>
<p>While Google Ads usually lets you opt in or out of partner sites, more and more campaign types (like <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/05/01/is-performance-max-right-for-you">Performance Max</a> and conversion-focused video campaigns) force you into all available placements.</p>
<p>Another key difference here is that Meta Ads on Facebook and Instagram must be linked to a page or profile. This means that whenever your ad shows up, users can click on your <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2015/02/20/call-to-action-buttons">call to action</a>, but they can also engage with the post or visit your social profile.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/meta-ads-engagement.jpg" alt="meta ads example with engagement" width="505" height="598" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-75216" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/meta-ads-engagement.jpg 505w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/meta-ads-engagement-480x568.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 505px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>You can see nine people engaged with this ad by adding a reaction.</em></p>
<p>Contrast this with Google Ads, where Google <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/07/13/google-advertiser-verification">has only just started verifying advertisers</a> and displaying a business name alongside search ads. Given that this feature is still in beta, I recommend that at least one of your headline assets should always include your brand name, since the ‚Äúcall to action‚Äù in a search ad is simply clicking on the headline.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/google-ads-account-verification-ad-example.jpg" alt="google advertiser verification badge" width="831" height="509" class="aligncenter wp-image-73704 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/google-ads-account-verification-ad-example.jpg 831w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/google-ads-account-verification-ad-example-480x294.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 831px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>¬†</em><em>An <a href="https://www.seroundtable.com/google-ads-gold-verification-badge-35279.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">example</a> of the Google Ads verification badge.</em></p>
<div id="budgets"></div>
<h2>Meta Ads vs. Google Ads: Budgets</h2>
<p>There are several differences in the way budgets are set up and spent in Meta Ads vs. Google Ads.</p>
<h3>Where do you set the budget?</h3>
<p>In a Meta Ads campaign, your budget is set at the ad set level. You have the option to turn on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/meta-advantage-plus">Advantage</a> campaign budget, which lets all ad sets within a campaign share a single budget.</p>
<p>In a Google Ads campaign, your budget is set at the <em>campaign</em> level; there is no option for ad group-level budgets.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/google-ads-total-campaign-budget.jpg" alt="google ads campaign level budget" width="936" height="439" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-75213" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/google-ads-total-campaign-budget.jpg 936w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/google-ads-total-campaign-budget-480x225.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 936px, 100vw" /></p>
<h3>What kind of budget can I use?</h3>
<p>Meta Ads lets you set daily budgets or lifetime budgets, whereas Google Ads campaigns only use daily budgets‚Äîexcept for video campaigns.</p>
<p>The mentality here is that most Google Ads campaigns are designed to be ‚Äúalways on,‚Äù whereas Meta Ads campaigns are more frequently flighted. With either platform, in order to set a lifetime budget, your campaign will need to have an end date.</p>
<h3>Why is it blowing my budget?!</h3>
<p>Even if you do select a daily budget, don‚Äôt expect the same outcome on both platforms! Meta Ads and Google Ads both treat your daily budget as an <em>average</em> daily budget, not a <em>maximum</em> daily budget.</p>
<p>Meta Ads may spend up to 25% more than your daily budget on a given day, but over the course of a week, won‚Äôt spend more than 7 times your daily budget. Effectively, your ‚Äúdaily budget‚Äù on Meta Ads is a <em>weekly</em> budget.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/meta-ads-budget-set.jpg" alt="where to set daily or weekly budget in meta ads" width="748" height="443" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-75217" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/meta-ads-budget-set.jpg 748w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/meta-ads-budget-set-480x284.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 748px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Google Ads may spend up to 100% more than your daily budget on a given day, but over the course of a month, won‚Äôt spend more than 30.4 times your daily budget. Effectively, your ‚Äúdaily budget‚Äù on Google Ads is a <em>monthly</em> budget.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/google-ads-daily-budget.jpg" alt="google ads set daily budget screen" width="936" height="364" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-75212" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/google-ads-daily-budget.jpg 936w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/google-ads-daily-budget-480x187.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 936px, 100vw" /></p>
<div class='et-box et-shadow'>
					<div class='et-box-content'><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/1f4b0.png" alt="üí∞" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> Are you making the most of your Google Ads budget? Find out with our <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/google-adwords?cid=Web_Any_InContentTextLink_PPC_AWGrader_AWGrader">Google Ads Performance Grader</a>.</div></div>
<div id="creative"></div>
<h2>Meta Ads vs. Google Ads: Creative</h2>
<p>In Meta Ads, your <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2016/05/23/facebook-ad-examples">ad creative</a> consists of a headline, description, primary text, and then your images or video. While you can have multiple headlines, descriptions, etc. within one ad, it‚Äôs more common to do ad testing by creating multiple standalone ads.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/facebook-ads-not-converting-copy-example-1.jpg" alt="facebook ads not converting - facebook ads copy example" width="496" height="650" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-73100" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/facebook-ads-not-converting-copy-example-1.jpg 496w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/facebook-ads-not-converting-copy-example-1-480x629.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 496px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Contrast this with Google Ads, where responsive is the new normal. What does responsive mean? In Google‚Äôs world, a <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/03/11/responsive-search-ads-new-default-google-ads">responsive ad</a> contains a wide variety of assets that Google can piece together to create thousands of different combinations. For example, a <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/04/05/responsive-search-ad-copy">Responsive Search Ad</a> can have up to 15 different headlines and four different descriptions.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/responsive-search-ads-combinations-report.png" alt="responsive search ads combinations report" width="720" height="395" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-65275" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/responsive-search-ads-combinations-report.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/responsive-search-ads-combinations-report-480x263.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Speaking of descriptions, think of the primary text in a Meta Ad as equivalent to a description in a Google Ad. This is where you can actually use full sentences and provide more details about your products or services.</p>
<div id="targeting"></div>
<h2>Meta Ads vs. Google Ads: Targeting</h2>
<p>Here are a few differences in the targeting options available in Meta Ads vs. Google Ads.</p>
<h3>Lookalikes</h3>
<p>You‚Äôre probably familiar with the concept of a <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/facebook-lookalike-audiences">lookalike audience</a> (Meta Ads verbiage) or a similar segment (Google Ads verbiage). By adding this targeting to your campaign, you can reach new users who exhibit similar online behavior to your existing users.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/lookalike-audience-meta-ads.jpg" alt="how to set up lookalike audience in meta ads" width="791" height="597" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-75218" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/lookalike-audience-meta-ads.jpg 791w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/lookalike-audience-meta-ads-480x362.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 791px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Unfortunately, <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/12/13/google-sunsetting-similar-audiences">Google Ads has said <em>Sayonara</em> to the similar segment</a>; you can no longer add them to campaigns, and as of August 2023, they will stop serving entirely. However, lookalikes are alive and well in Meta Ads, and a common prospecting tactic for those just getting started on the platform.</p>
<h3>Audience expansion</h3>
<p>If you‚Äôve ever run paid ads, regardless of platform, you know that <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/05/23/google-marketing-live">automation is taking over</a>. Both Google Ads and Meta Ads will push you hard to automate your audience targeting!</p>
<p>Google Ads calls this <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/07/22/google-ads-optimized-targeting">Optimized Targeting</a>, Meta Ads calls this <a href="https://www.facebook.com/business/help/128066880933676?id=176276233019487" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Advantage Detailed Targeting</a>. Both settings are often turned on by default and give the platform permission to show your ads to people beyond your audience selections who it thinks are likely to convert. I recommend testing it; sometimes it works well, sometimes it doesn‚Äôt but you never know until you try. (Learn more about <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/meta-advantage-vs-manual-settings">Meta Advantage+</a>)</p>
<div class='et-box et-shadow'>
					<div class='et-box-content'>How do your Facebook ads stack up against your competitors? Find out with our <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/facebook-advertising?cid=Web_Any_InContentTextLink_PPC_FBGrader_FBGrader">Free Facebook Ads Performance Grader</a>!</div></div>
<div id="reporting"></div>
<h2>Meta Ads vs. Google Ads: Reporting</h2>
<p>If you are looking for reporting transparency, Google Ads definitely wins this showdown.</p>
<h3>Transparency</h3>
<p>In Meta Ads, reporting is provided at the campaign, ad set, or ad level. Practically, this means that if you add multiple audiences to the same ad set, you will not know how each of those audiences performs, just how the ad set performs overall. While you can create separate ad sets for each audience, this potentially brings other issues with budget, reach, etc.</p>
<p>In Google Ads, reporting is provided at much more granular levels. If you add <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/keywords?cid=Web_Any_InContentTextLink_Keywords_KWTool">multiple keywords</a>, placements, audiences, etc. to the same ad group, you will still get detailed reporting on how each piece of your targeting puzzle performs. This is immensely helpful for <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2020/08/24/google-ads-optimization">optimization</a>.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/google-ads-asset-report-associations-metrics.png" alt="google ads assets report - metrics available in the associations view" width="720" height="333" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-64511" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/google-ads-asset-report-associations-metrics.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/google-ads-asset-report-associations-metrics-480x222.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<h3>Default attribution windows</h3>
<p>The default attribution setting when creating a campaign in Meta Ads is seven-day click or one-day view. This means that once someone clicks on your ad, if they convert within seven days, that campaign will take credit. Similarly, if someone views but does not click on your ad, then converts within one day, the campaign will also take credit. This is why your <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/06/23/google-analytics-4-vs-universal-analytics">Google Analytics reporting</a> will never line up with your Meta Ads Manager reporting; Google Analytics can‚Äôt ‚Äúsee‚Äù those view-through conversions.</p>
<p>Google Ads generally does not include view-through conversions by default. However, the default click conversion window in Google Ads Manager is 30 days. This is why your Google Analytics reporting will never line up with your Google Ads reporting, either; Google Ads will keep ‚Äúadding‚Äù <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/02/08/google-ads-conversion-tracking-mistakes">conversions</a> over the course of the month.</p>
<div class='et-box et-shadow'>
					<div class='et-box-content'><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/2764.png" alt="‚ù§" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> Find out how Meta Ads + Google Ads can make the most of your marketing in our free guide &gt;&gt; <a href="https://marketing.wordstream.com/WSLIQContentDLWebsite4WaysToMakeGoogleFBWorkBetterTogether.html?cid=Web_Any_BlogInContent_PPC_4WaysBetterTogether_Download">4 Ways to Make Facebook &amp; Google the Perfect Pair</a></div></div>
<h2>Key differences between Google Ads and Meta Ads</h2>
<p>When evaluating the different capabilities of <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/facebook-vs-google">Google Ads and Meta Ads</a>, think of them as first cousins rather than distant relatives. They share similar DNA but have diverged over time due to different priorities. If you‚Äôre well versed in one platform and looking to get started in the other, this is a friendly reminder to do your due diligence (like reading this article!) so that you don‚Äôt get tripped up.</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/08/15/meta-ads-vs-google-ads">Meta Ads vs. Google Ads: 6 Key Differences (+Which Is Better?)</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
