		<title>How to Make Google Ads Automation Work for You (Dos &#038; Don&#8217;ts From a Pro)</title>
		<link>https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/03/02/guide-to-automation-in-google-ads</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Jyll Saskin Gales]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Thu, 02 Mar 2023 15:48:24 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Google Ads]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://www.wordstream.com/?p=70601</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[<p>The dos and don'ts of properly using automation for bidding, targeting, and ad creative.</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/03/02/guide-to-automation-in-google-ads">How to Make Google Ads Automation Work for You (Dos &#038; Don&#8217;ts From a Pro)</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><em>Automation in Google Ads has its pros and cons, depending on what feature you&#8217;re dealing with and which PPC practitioner you&#8217;re talking to. Empiric Marketing LLC founder <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/01/04/google-ads-automation">Brett McHale shares his perspectives here on Google Ads automation</a>, and now, Jyll Saskin Gales shares hers!</em></p>
<p>&#8212;&#8212;-</p>
<p>Is Google Ads automation your friend or foe? Even as a self-proclaimed machine learning lover, I will admit that ‚Äújust automate it‚Äù is not <em>always</em> the right answer. In this guide to automation in Google Ads, I&#8217;m going to cover these three areas so you can make the best choices for your ad account and your business:</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="#bidding">Automated bidding</a></li>
<li><a href="#targeting">Automated targeting</a></li>
<li><a href="#creative">Automated ad creative</a></li>
</ul>
<p>Let&#8217;s get started!</p>
<h2>How to succeed with Google Ads automated bidding</h2>
<p><a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2018/12/19/google-ads-automated-bidding">Automated bidding</a> is a great way to start trusting the ‚ÄúGoogle machines‚Äù to automate part of your ad buying process.</p>
<p>Today, there are few use cases where manual bidding would make sense over automated bidding, or what Google Ads calls ‚ÄúSmart Bidding.‚Äù Why? Because the purpose of Google Ads isn‚Äôt to achieve a certain cost per click; it‚Äôs to achieve <em>business results</em>: revenue, profitability, return on investment.</p>
<p>Because Google knows so much more about its users than you do, and can incorporate millions of signals into determining your bids for every single auction, let the machine do what it does best: Smart Bidding. There are four main metrics you can bid for in Google Ads, and two ways of leveraging Smart Bidding. Let‚Äôs break it down.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Clicks:</strong> Maximize clicks*</li>
<li><strong>Conversions:</strong> Maximize conversions, Target CPA</li>
<li><strong>Conversion value:</strong> Maximize conversion value, Target ROAS</li>
<li><strong>Impressions / Impression Share:</strong> Target CPM*, Target Impression Share*</li>
</ul>
<p>In other words, when choosing an automated bid strategy for your Google Ads campaign, you need to let the system know what kind of results you‚Äôre looking to get: clicks, conversions, conversion value or impressions. Then, Google can do what it does best and set your individual bids for you to achieve that goal.</p>
<p><em><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/google-ads-bidding-strategies-chart.png" alt="what is target roas - google ads bidding strategies chart" width="700" height="430" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-58094" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/google-ads-bidding-strategies-chart.png 700w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/google-ads-bidding-strategies-chart-480x295.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 700px, 100vw" /></em></p>
<p><em>*Note that Google considers those that I‚Äôve starred to be automated bidding strategies, not ‚ÄúSmart Bidding‚Äù strategies, because they ‚Äúdon‚Äôt include auction time bidding.‚Äù For simplicity‚Äôs sake, I‚Äôve included all automated bid strategies together here, both ‚ÄúSmart‚Äù and ‚Äúnot Smart‚Äù</em></p>
<h3>&#8220;Maximize&#8221; vs &#8220;Target&#8221; bid strategies</h3>
<p>Once you decide what kind of results you‚Äôre looking for, then it‚Äôs time to determine how you want the automated bidding to perform. There are two main buckets of Smart Bidding strategies in Google Ads.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Maximize</strong>, as in ‚ÄúMaximize conversions‚Äù or ‚ÄúMaximize conversion value‚Äù<strong><br />
</strong>Here, you have a <strong>fixed budget</strong> and want Google Ads to drive as many results (clicks, conversions, etc.) as possible within that budget, <em>regardless of efficiency.</em><strong><br />
</strong></li>
<li><strong>Target</strong>, as in ‚ÄúTarget CPA‚Äù or ‚ÄúTarget ROAS‚Äù<br />
Here, you have a <strong>fixed efficiency</strong> level you must hit (CPA or ROAS), and want Google Ads to do whatever it can to achieve that efficiency, <strong><em>regardless of budget. </em></strong>Google Ads will still stay within <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/02/14/google-ads-budgeting-strategies">your budget</a>, of course, but will prompt you to increase the budget if additional opportunity exists.</li>
</ul>
<p>When in doubt, I recommend using the <strong>Maximize conversions</strong> bid strategy. It‚Äôs hard to go wrong with that as your starting point.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/maximize-conversion-value-google-ads-bidding.png" alt="maximize conversion value bidding in google ads" width="601" height="392" class="aligncenter wp-image-65325" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/maximize-conversion-value-google-ads-bidding.png 601w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/maximize-conversion-value-google-ads-bidding-480x313.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 601px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Keep in mind that even with automated bidding, you still need to monitor and manage your bids! Here are our <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/01/17/google-ads-bid-management">tips for effective bid management in a world of automated bidding</a>.</p>
<h2>How to win with automated targeting in Search campaigns</h2>
<p>Automated targeting is the next frontier in scaling your reach with Google Ads. No matter how talented you are at picking the perfect keywords, or leveraging the exact right audiences, you&#8217;re going to be missing opportunities if you go about targeting manually.</p>
<p>Why? Because with all of its data and machine learning, Google knows so much more about its users (aka your potential customers) than you do. Here are two ways to use automation when targeting your Search campaigns:</p>
<h3>Dynamic ad groups</h3>
<p>Just like a Shopping campaign uses your Merchant Center feed instead of keywords to match the right queries to your ads, a Dynamic ad group uses your website instead of keywords to match the right queries to your ads. And just like a Shopping campaign, you can review your <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/09/16/google-ads-search-terms-report-changes">Search terms report</a> to see which queries you‚Äôve shown ads on, and<a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2018/06/06/negative-keyword-guide"> add negative keywords</a> as needed.</p>
<p>When setting up a Dynamic ad group, you can use your entire website or specific pages as the ‚ÄúDynamic ad target‚Äù</p>
<p><strong>I‚Äôve got a quick and easy trick to figure out whether Dynamic ad groups may work well for you: </strong></p>
<p>Go to Keyword Planner &gt; Start with a website, and then type in the URL or URLs for which you&#8217;d like to use a Dynamic ad group.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/keyword-planner-enter-website.png" alt="google ads keyword planner enter website" width="720" height="367" class="size-full wp-image-70604 aligncenter" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/keyword-planner-enter-website.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/keyword-planner-enter-website-480x245.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>If the keyword recommendations that come back are highly relevant, then go ahead and automate your targeting with a Dynamic ad group.</p>
<p>However, if the keyword suggestions that come back are not relevant, you probably aren‚Äôt ready to leverage a Dynamic ad group, yet, and you should also speak with an <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2020/09/15/small-business-seo-services">SEO specialist</a> to fix that! You can also review our <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/seo">guide to SEO here</a>.</p>
<h3>Broad match keywords</h3>
<p>Another way to leverage automated targeting in Search campaigns is by using broad match keywords. I know, I know, Google wouldn‚Äôt classify their <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/06/06/broad-match-smart-bidding">beloved broad match</a> this way, but effectively, this is what broad match does! You provide your keywords, and then Google finds hundreds of <em>other</em> queries that it deems relevant to your keywords.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/google-ads-budget-strategies-keyword-match-types.png" alt="google ads budget strategies - keyword match types" width="720" height="443" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-70241" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/google-ads-budget-strategies-keyword-match-types.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/google-ads-budget-strategies-keyword-match-types-480x295.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<div class='et-box et-shadow'>
					<div class='et-box-content'><p><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/1f511.png" alt="üîë" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> <strong>Looking for keywords?</strong></p>
<p>You can use our <strong><a href="https://www.wordstream.com/keywords?cid=Web_Any_InContentTextLink_Keywords_KWTool">Free Keyword Tool</a> </strong>to find keywords for your PPC campaigns!</p></div></div>
<h2>How to hit the bullseye with automated targeting in audience-based campaigns</h2>
<p>When setting up a <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/06/12/google-discovery-ads-vs-display">Display, Discovery</a>, or Video campaign, you likely have your <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/09/21/google-ads-audience-targeting-cheat-sheet">various audiences picked out</a>. However, Google can build on that for you to automate your targeting via <strong>Optimized targeting</strong> or <strong>Audience expansion</strong>.</p>
<h3>Optimized targeting</h3>
<p><a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/07/22/google-ads-optimized-targeting">Optimized targeting</a> analyzes your converters, and then finds new users who exhibit similar online behavior to those converters. Think of it like a Similar segment for your converters‚Äîand not a moment too soon, since <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/12/13/google-sunsetting-similar-audiences">Similar segments are being deprecated</a>.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/optimized-targeting-google-ads.png" alt="how optimized targeting works in google ads" width="720" height="405" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-68683" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/optimized-targeting-google-ads.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/optimized-targeting-google-ads-480x270.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<h3>Audience expansion</h3>
<p>Audience expansion is the equivalent feature for reach-focused Video campaigns. When turned on, it will find additional Google audience segments that are similar to those you‚Äôve selected, and then target them as well.</p>
<p>I like to start my audience campaigns with Optimized targeting turned on, and then see how it performs. If after a few weeks it outperforms my audience selections, great! And if not, it‚Äôs easy to turn off with one click.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/google-ads-audience-expansion.png" alt="google ads audience expansion" width="720" height="294" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-68303" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/google-ads-audience-expansion.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/google-ads-audience-expansion-480x196.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Of course, if you run an <strong>App campaign</strong>, you have no choice but to use fully automated targeting, as you don‚Äôt get to pick any keywords or audiences. And while <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/07/05/performance-max-tips"><strong>Performance Max campaigns</strong></a> do let you pick an <strong>Audience signal</strong>, you‚Äôre essentially defaulted into Optimized targeting, but at least you can check the Insights tab to see which audiences Google Ads has found for you!</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/07/performance-max-audience-signals.png" alt="performance max audience signal setup" width="720" height="374" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-62617" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/07/performance-max-audience-signals.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/07/performance-max-audience-signals-480x249.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<h2>How to make the most of automated creative</h2>
<p>Let‚Äôs say you‚Äôre leveraging automated bidding and automated targeting. That may be enough for you, and the general feeling I get from the industry these days is: Enough already!</p>
<p>Well, for Google, there‚Äôs no such thing as enough automation.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/headlines-google-ads-automation.png" alt="headlines about google ads automation" width="720" height="472" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-69380" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/headlines-google-ads-automation.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/headlines-google-ads-automation-480x315.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>The final frontier is automated creative, an area that‚Äôs seen plenty of changes recently with <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/09/02/google-sunsetting-expanded-text-ads">Responsive Search Ads instead of Expanded Text Ads</a>, <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/09/16/google-ads-extensions-now-assets">‚ÄúAssets‚Äù instead of Extensions</a>, and the Google Ads Video Creator launch.</p>
<p>A good hint that Google Ads will be automating some ad creative for you is when you see the word ‚Äúdynamic.‚Äù For example, in a <strong>Dynamic ad group</strong> (explained above), Google Ads will create the right headlines for each user‚Äôs query. In <strong>Dynamic remarketing</strong> (explained below), Google Ads will show the right products in the ad for each user.</p>
<h3>Responsive ads</h3>
<p>No matter what <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/10/05/types-of-google-ads">type of Google ad</a> you&#8217;re running‚Äîbe it a Search ad, Display ad, Discovery ad, Video ad, Performance Max ad, or App ad, they will all be r<strong>esponsive ads</strong>. This means that you provide Google Ads with the building blocks of your ad, which Google calls ‚ÄúAssets‚Äù (headlines, descriptions, images, feed, videos, logos), and then Google tests hundreds of combinations to achieve your goals.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/how-responsive-search-ads-work.png" alt="types of google ads - how responsive search ads work" width="720" height="481" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-59791" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/how-responsive-search-ads-work.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/how-responsive-search-ads-work-480x321.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>You cannot opt out of responsive ads, which means you are already leveraging automated creative at its most basic level if you‚Äôre <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/03/21/how-to-run-google-ads">running Google Ads</a>.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><span><div class='et-box et-shadow'>
					<div class='et-box-content'><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/270d.png" alt="‚úç" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> <strong>Need help writing headlines for your responsive ads? </strong></span></p>
<p><span><strong>Free guide!</strong> &gt;&gt;</span> <strong><a href="https://marketing.wordstream.com/WSContentDLWebBlogInContentTextLinkTrickstoClicks.html?cid=Web_Blog_InContent_TextLink_TrickstoClicks_Download" class="waffle-rich-text-link">10 Tricks to Get the Click: How to Write Exceptional PPC Ad Copy (with Examples!)</a></strong></p>
<p><span></div></div></span></p>
<h3>Dynamic assets (formerly known as extensions)</h3>
<p>In addition to responsive ads, where you still pick your assets and then Google automates how they are shown to the end user, there are also plenty of auto-generated, or ‚Äúdynamic‚Äù assets, to opt into.</p>
<p>For example, <strong>Dynamic image assets</strong> (formerly Dynamic image extensions) give Google Ads permission to pull images from your website and insert them as add-ons to your ads.</p>
<p>And you‚Äôve probably heard of <strong>Dynamic remarketing</strong>, which is when Google Ads creates Display ads that show users products they‚Äôve previously viewed on your website. This is also automated creative, since it is both responsive and dynamic, customizing the content and layout for each user based on your Merchant Center feed.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/dynamic-remarketing.png" alt="dynamic remarketing" width="720" height="259" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-70532" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/dynamic-remarketing.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/dynamic-remarketing-480x173.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://faq.businesstech.fr/en/faq/225-whats-the-difference-between-classic-remarketing-and-dynamic-remarketing" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Image source</em></a></p>
<h3>Performance Max automated video creation</h3>
<p>The final frontier in automated creative is not just going responsive or dynamic, but rather letting Google <em>create your assets for you</em>.</p>
<p>I know. It feels uncomfortable. But we already have a sneak peek at what this looks like in a Performance Max campaign. If you do not provide any video assets in an Asset group, Google Ads will automatically create videos for you. And they‚Äôre pretty ugly! But remember, just because something looks good, it doesn&#8217;t mean it converts well. Ultimately, Google has the same desire as you: <em>achieve your business goals</em>.</p>
<p>If you&#8217;re not ready to let Google create videos for you just yet, I recommend checking out the new video creator tool in Google Ads, so you can at least choose your own template, text, images, and music.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/google-ads-video-creator.png" alt="google ads video creator" width="720" height="434" class="size-full wp-image-70656 aligncenter" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/google-ads-video-creator.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/google-ads-video-creator-480x289.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>You can find more <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/04/20/performance-max-pros-cons">pros and cons to Performance Max campaigns here</a>.</p>
<h2>The number one factor in succeeding with automation in Google Ads</h2>
<p>Whether you‚Äôre testing automated bidding, targeting or creative, the most important success factor is not how smart (or dumb) Google is, it‚Äôs your <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/02/08/google-ads-conversion-tracking-mistakes">conversion tracking</a>.</p>
<ul>
<li>Automated bidding only works if Google has good conversion data to learn from.</li>
<li>Automated targeting only works if Google knows who&#8217;s converting and who&#8217;s not.</li>
<li>Automated creative only works if Google knows which assets result in conversions.</li>
</ul>
<p>The most important success factor to make sure that any kind of automation is going to drive good results for your business is having <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/08/30/google-ads-conversion-tracking">solid, full-funnel conversion tracking in place</a>.</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/03/02/guide-to-automation-in-google-ads">How to Make Google Ads Automation Work for You (Dos &#038; Don&#8217;ts From a Pro)</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
			</item>
		<item>
		<title>How to Combat Costs With Google Ads Custom Segments</title>
		<link>https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/10/18/google-ads-custom-segments</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Jyll Saskin Gales]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Tue, 18 Oct 2022 20:27:30 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Google Ads]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://www.wordstream.com/?p=65508</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[<p>Learn how to wield the power of this underused Google Ads feature.</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/10/18/google-ads-custom-segments">How to Combat Costs With Google Ads Custom Segments</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>When it comes to <span><a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/09/21/google-ads-audience-targeting-cheat-sheet">Google Ads audience targeting</a>,</span> there are a number of different audiences you can use. They can be bucketed into three main types: Google‚Äôs audience segments, &#8220;your data&#8221; segments, and &#8220;custom&#8221; segments.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/google-ads-audience-targeting-cheat-sheet.png" alt="google ads audience targeting cheat sheet" width="720" height="538" class="size-full wp-image-64681 aligncenter" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/google-ads-audience-targeting-cheat-sheet.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/google-ads-audience-targeting-cheat-sheet-480x359.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Custom segments are what I want to dive into today, because in my opinion, they&#8217;re one of the most powerful and underutilized features in Google Ads. Read on to find out:</p>
<ul>
<li>What Google Ads custom segments are</li>
<li>Why you should use them</li>
<li>How to create custom segments in Google Ads</li>
</ul>
<h2>What are custom segments in Google Ads?</h2>
<p>Google Ads custom segments let you leverage Google‚Äôs proprietary data about its users in ways that are unique to your business. You can create custom segments using up to three criteria:</p>
<ol>
<li>The interests and products/services people are <strong>searching</strong> for</li>
<li>The types of <strong>websites</strong> people browse</li>
<li>The types of <strong>apps</strong> people use</li>
</ol>
<p>By &#8220;up to&#8221; three criteria, this means that you can target just one of those criteria or any combination of two or three.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/google-ads-audience-targeting-custom-segments.png" alt="google ads targeting - custom segment example" width="720" height="551" class="size-full wp-image-64674 aligncenter" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/google-ads-audience-targeting-custom-segments.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/google-ads-audience-targeting-custom-segments-480x367.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>This custom segment targets all three criteria: interests, types of websites, and apps.</em></p>
<p>Once you create a custom segment, you can add it to your Display, Discovery, or Video campaigns. You can also add custom segments to your audience signals for <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/07/05/performance-max-tips">Performance Max campaigns</a>, which Google considers a best practice (and I agree).</p>
<h2>Why you should use custom segments in Google Ads</h2>
<p>There are two main reasons why I believe custom segments are so darn useful.</p>
<h3>Highly specific targeting</h3>
<p>First, while there are thousands of <span>Google Ads audience targeting</span> choices, many advertisers are just not able to find the right ones for them. For example, what if <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/05/11/target-audience">your target audience</a> is digital marketing professionals? Or doctors? Or people who are alums of Ivy League universities?</p>
<p>Custom segments let you create the perfect audience for your needs by leveraging Google‚Äôs immense data about user behavior based on their searches, the websites they visit, and the apps they use.</p>
<h3>Lower competition &amp; costs</h3>
<p>Custom segments can <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/02/21/how-to-save-money-google-ads">save you money on your Google Ads</a>. Since you‚Äôre the only one who will have this custom segment in your account (after all, it is custom!), competition may be lower, which means potentially <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/why-google-ad-costs-are-rising-in-2025">lower ad costs</a>.</p>
<p>Also, we know that Search CPCs are rising, and Search ads are getting more and more expensive each year (<a href="https://www.wordstream.com/online-advertising-benchmarks">check our benchmarks!</a>) In comparison, CPCs on Discovery are generally quite affordable.</p>
<p>Custom segments allow you to reach people who have been searching for your keywords, just not in the moment they‚Äôre actually searching. Right people + different time = still powerful results. Create a Discovery campaign targeting a custom segment of your <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2014/06/30/commercial-intent-keywords">top Search keywords</a>, and watch some magic happen!</p>
<div class='et-box et-shadow'>
					<div class='et-box-content'><p><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/1f4b0.png" alt="üí∞" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> <strong>Find opportunities to save money in Google Ads with the</strong> <strong><a href="https://www.wordstream.com/google-adwords?cid=Web_Any_InContentTextLink_PPC_AWGrader_AWGrader">Free Google Ads Grader</a></strong>.</p></div></div>
<h2>How to create a Custom segment in Google Ads</h2>
<p>To create custom segments in Google Ads, go to Tools &amp; Settings, and then select Audience Manager.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/google-ads-custom-segments-tools-settings.png" alt="google ads custom segments - audience manager" width="720" height="315" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-65513" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/google-ads-custom-segments-tools-settings.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/google-ads-custom-segments-tools-settings-480x210.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Choose the Custom segments tab:</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/google-ads-custom-segments-creation.png" alt="google ads custom segments tab" width="720" height="329" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-65514" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/google-ads-custom-segments-creation.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/google-ads-custom-segments-creation-480x219.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>You can then create a custom segment using one or any combination of these three criteria:</p>
<h3>1. Interests or behaviors</h3>
<p>You can create a custom segment to target people with specific interests or purchase intentions, or who have searched specific terms on Google.</p>
<p>For example, I‚Äôve run a YouTube campaign advertising my <span><a href="https://learn.jyll.ca/courses/insidegoogleads/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Google Ads course</a></span> targeted to a Custom segment of people who have searched for ‚Äúgoogle ads course,‚Äù ‚Äúadwords course,‚Äù ‚Äúlearn google ads,‚Äù ‚Äúgoogle ads training,‚Äù etc.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/google-ads-custom-segment-search-terms.png" alt="google ads custom segment creation from search terms" width="720" height="558" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-65516" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/google-ads-custom-segment-search-terms.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/google-ads-custom-segment-search-terms-480x372.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p><strong>Note! </strong>There‚Äôs one finicky little nuance to be aware of, though. If your custom segment includes a list of terms that people are searching for, this will only work as intended on Google-owned properties: Discovery and YouTube.</p>
<p>On the Display network and Video partner sites, your search terms will be treated as general ‚Äúinterests‚Äù rather than specific things people have searched for. So keep that in mind when <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/10/05/types-of-google-ads">picking your campaign type</a> and settings!</p>
<h3>2. Types of websites</h3>
<p>You can also create a custom segment based on the types of websites people browse.</p>
<p>For example, a business I was advising was trying to reach dentists and people who work in dental offices, so they targeted a custom segment of industry news-type websites for dentists.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/google-ads-custom-segments-sites.png" alt="google ads custom segments based on websites" width="720" height="553" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-65519" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/google-ads-custom-segments-sites.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/google-ads-custom-segments-sites-480x369.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<h3>3. Types of apps</h3>
<p>And finally, you can create a Custom segment based on the types of apps people use.</p>
<p>For example, if you want to reach small business owners using Google Ads, you can target a custom segment of people who have apps like Shopify, Wix, Etsy Seller, Ecwid Ecommerce, etc.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/google-ads-custom-segment-apps.png" alt="google ads custom segment creation from apps" width="720" height="554" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-65517" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/google-ads-custom-segment-apps.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/google-ads-custom-segment-apps-480x369.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<h2>Start using Google Ads custom segments</h2>
<p>Now can you see why I think Google Ads custom segments are underutilized? They&#8217;re a powerful way to target your prospects, reduce competition, and lower your costs. Use these tips and steps to start using them and getting more out of your budget!</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/10/18/google-ads-custom-segments">How to Combat Costs With Google Ads Custom Segments</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
